Summer Blizzard: F2Q 'Beat/Raise' Driven By Solid Core Consumption & Building Momentum In Emerging Solutions SNOW delivered strong F2Q results highlighted by product revenue of \(\) 1,090.5m\((+32\%)\) , solidly above mgmt. guidance of \(\) 1,035- 1,040m\((+25\%)\) and Street sets. of \(\) 1,040.6m\((+25\%)\) , and operating margins of \(11\%\) vs. mgmt. guidance and Street sets. of \(8\%\) . Management flagged that the beat was broad- based, as the core business remains very strong and areas like Iceberg and Al are beginning to contribute revenue - \(1,200+\) accounts are using Iceberg, 6,100+ accounts are using Al on a weekly basis (up from 5,200 in the prior quarter), and Al influenced nearly \(50\%\) of new logos won in the quarter. In terms of future quarters, F3Q26 product revenue guidance of \(\) 1,125- 1,130m\((+25 - 26\%)\) was ahead of Street expectations of \(\) 1,120.8m\((+24\%)\) , and mgmt. raised its full year FY26 product revenue guide to \(\) 4,395m\((+27\%)\) , up from prior mgmt. guidance of \(\) 4,325m\((+25\%)\) - while much of the 'raise' was a pull- forward of the F2Q beat, we believe the bump to full year revenue illustrates management's confidence in the durability of near- term demand and we would expect the F3Q guide has some conservatism baked in as the pace of consumption in F2Q was clearly ahead of SNOW's expectations.

Bottom line: We believe that the combination of accelerating revenue growth - now in the high \(20\%\) - driven by stabilization in the core and contributions from Al and Data Engineering workloads - and op. margin leverage can drive further multiple expansion from current levels. We continue to believe there is room for further upward revisions to guidance and Street sets. Maintain Outperform and move PT to \(\) 280\(\) (15x EV / CY27 revenue).

In terms of key takeaways, we would highlight the following: (1) The total number of customers grew to 12,062 from 11,529 q/q, and the number of customers with TTM product revenue of \(\) 1m+\(grew from 604 to 654 q/q. G2K customer count grew from 736 to 751; (2) Net revenue retention rate landed at 125\% vs. 124\% in the prior quarter and came in ahead of our estimate of 122\%; (3) The cohort of digital native Al companies makes up 1.2\% of revenue, with OpenAl making up less than 1\% of revenue, alleviating some of the risk around Al customer concentration; (4) 40\% of customers are using stable edges, up from 39\% q/q; and (5) Azure was SNOW's fastest growing cloud with 40\% growth.

Recapping the quarter: Total revenue of \(\) 1,090m\((+32\% y / y)\) came in above our/Street estimates of \(\) 1,039/1,041m\(. Operating margins landed at 11\%\), above our/Street estimates of 7.9\% / 8.2\%. Adjusted FCF landed at\) \ \(67.3m\) (6% revenue margin) vs. Street estimates of \(\) 397.6m\(. RPO landed at\) \ \(6.9bn\) , up 33\% y/y.

**What we liked:** (1) Azure was SNOW's fastest growing cloud with 40% y/y growth as the partnership with Microsoft has improved, and mgmt. believes that MSFT's strong presence in Europe can help with growth in the region; (2) NRR accelerated to 125% from 124% q/q, demonstrating stability in the core as well as expanding AI / Data Engineering use cases; and (3) Emerging use cases are gaining traction: 1,200+ accounts are using Iceberg, 6,100+ accounts are using AI on a weekly basis (up from 5,200 in the prior quarter), and AI influenced nearly 50% of new logos won in the quarter.

**In terms of key takeaways,** **we** **would** **highlight** **the** **following:** (1) The total number of customers grew to 12,062 from 11,529 q/q, and the number of customers with TTM product revenue of $1mn+ grew from 604 to 654 q/q. G2K customer count grew from 736 to 751; (2) Net revenue retention rate landed at 125% vs. 124% in the prior quarter and came in ahead of our estimate of 122%; (3) The cohort of digital native AI companies makes up 1.2% of revenue, with OpenAI making up less than 1% of revenue, alleviating some of the risk around AI customer concentration; (4) 40% of customers are using stable edges, up from 39% q/q; and (5) Azure was SNOW's fastest growing cloud with 40% growth.

**What we have our eye on:** (1) The cohort of digital native AI companies makes up 1.2% of revenue, with OpenAI making up less than 1% of revenue, alleviating some of the risk around AI customer concentration. We believe that SNOW has a strong base of durable, enterprise customers in stable industries. G2K customers grew from 736 to 751 q/q; (2) While mgmt. guides conservatively and much of the FY26 'raise' was pull-forward of the F2Q beat, we believe the bump to full year revenue illustrates management's confidence in the durability of near-term demand and we would expect the F3Q guide has some conservatism baked in given the consumption strength seen in 2Q; and (3) Adjusted FCF margins were 6% in the quarter as mgmt. maintained its full year guide of 25%.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories.
